Cabins follows an interesting structure. It contains an alphanumeric category, followed by a number, followed by another alphanumeric category. From the prompt - we see that the logic is deck/num/side. This variable would be treated as a categorical variable if we do not engineer it a bit. In a basic logistic classification model we would treat each of these cabins as a categorical variable. As shown below, there are way too cabins for this to make logical sense. We make the decision to break apart this data into three different variables, Deck, Num and Side.

Conclusions of Basic Data Checks

  • We have widespread 'nan' values throughout our dataset, both on categorical variables as well as continious variables. We will likely have to decide how to account for those variables in our modeling.
  • We do have repeat passenger names, but they are not likely to be a data-related issue. Rather, they are truly passengers with the same name, who are different individuals
  • We do not have repeat Passenger IDs
  • There are too many cabins included in our dataset. We have rationalized the field into 3 different fields: Deck, Number and Side.

Handling nan values¶

As noted, there are many records with nan values in various fields. We need to clean those up before we implement our modeling approach
Our options:
A) Ignore any record with nan completely
B) Ignore entries with nan categorical variables
C) Ignore entries with nan continious variables
D) Fill in continious variables with logical imputed value (0, median, regression, average, etc.)
E) Fill in categorical variables with logical imputed value (mode, logistic regression)
F) Some combination of B, C, D, E

First off, it is unlikely to be a wise move to drop all records with nan values. The number of records w/ NaNs are considerable (~24%) of our dataset. At that amount of records, we could unintentionally be ommitting certain sub-populations from our training which would be included in the actual test data set, causing poor performance.

Decision: We make the decision to impute values for our nan values. I'll note that this is part of the art vs. science of model building. If the performance of the model is poor, this would be a good place to revisit to try and improve our modeling.

Handling Continious Variables

In this case, we decide to fill in continious variables with a 0 value - as the majority of those fields are related to spending habits of individuals. The one field of concern is that of "age", which we will have to handle differently, by imputing the average of the rest of the population.

In [44]:
#handle 'spend' vars
spend_vars = [['RoomService','FoodCourt','ShoppingMall','Spa','VRDeck']]
zero_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value = 0)
for x in spend_vars:
    train_data[x] = zero_imputer.fit_transform(train_data[x])
#handle age var
mean_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
train_data['Age'] = mean_imputer.fit_transform(train_data['Age'].values.reshape(-1, 1))

Handling Categorical Variables

We can impute the categorical variables using a simple mode method. Additional methods include knn_imputation and even building logistic regression models within our dataset, but we attempt our first pass using mode.

Removal of irrelevant variables¶

At this point it is worth noting that we will not be using several variables in our modeling:
1) PassengerID - Unique ID for each record. Identifier that is not relevant for our modeling.
2) Cabin - Feature that was engineered into others
3) Number - The room number, the numbering sequence method is unknown and therefore difficult to implement into our model. Additionally, categorical variables 'deck' and 'side' contain similar information.
4) Name - similar concept to PassengerID, this is not relevant.
5) has_nans - working column that we do not need.

Formalizing Data Processing¶

There are three steps to our transformations and data cleansing that we have performed:

1) We transform the Cabin Field into different features
2) We impute data for both continuous variables and categorical variables
3) We drop irrelevant features for our modeling

We can create a quick function that performs this process so that we don't have to re-code everything on a go-forward basis.

In [60]:
def process_data(df_train = pd.DataFrame(), df_test = pd.DataFrame()):
    #establish our variables
    spend_vars = [['RoomService','FoodCourt','ShoppingMall','Spa','VRDeck']]
    cat_vars = [['HomePlanet', 'CryoSleep', 'Destination','VIP','Deck','Side']]
    
    #transform cabin field and adjust the 'nan' strings
    df_train[['Deck', 'Number','Side']] = df_train['Cabin'].apply(lambda x: pd.Series(str(x).split("/")))
    df_train = df_train.replace('nan', np.nan)
    
    df_test[['Deck', 'Number','Side']] = df_test['Cabin'].apply(lambda x: pd.Series(str(x).split("/")))
    df_test = df_test.replace('nan', np.nan)
    
    #handle 'spend' vars
    zero_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value = 0)
    for x in spend_vars:
        df_train[x] = zero_imputer.fit_transform(df_train[x])
        df_test[x] = zero_imputer.fit_transform(df_test[x])
        
    #handle age var
    mean_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
    df_train['Age'] = mean_imputer.fit_transform(df_train['Age'].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    df_test['Age'] = mean_imputer.transform(df_test['Age'].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    
    mode_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
    for x in cat_vars:
        df_train[x] = mode_imputer.fit_transform(df_train[x])
        df_test[x] = mode_imputer.transform(df_test[x])
        
    #remove unnecessary columns 
    remove_list = ['PassengerId','Name','Number']
    df_test.drop(columns = remove_list, inplace = True) 
    df_train.drop(columns = remove_list, inplace = True)
    return df_test, df_train

Commentary and Critique of Approach¶

There are a couple of key ommissions in our process that I would like to call out.

First, we do not leverage any kind of robust pipeline methodology in order to formalize our data transformations and preparations. In a real-world scenario we would like to formalize and document this process so that different batches of data can be more easily inputed and executed on. Scikitlearn has several features to help with this process, aptly named "Pipelines"

Additionally, we do not do any kind of feature limitation or selection during our model-building. In the real-world, it is likely that we would like to reduce the number of features necessary for our model to run. Simple is often better and more interpretable. I would use BIC or AIC to compare the models performance and work to reduce the number of features necessary for top performance.

Finally, our EDA is relatively light. We should also explore covariances and the relationships between different variables (a categorical features impact on a continuous variable, for example). Additionally, our imputation methodology is quite basic. If we really wanted to improve upon our performance, it is likely that we would have to spend more time thinking through our imputations and making sure that they followed some kind of logic given what we see from the other records. For example, our assumption that all NaNs in spend are zero might be correct, but we could use a much more complex imputation methodology, like linear regression to make an estimate of that field.

Much of this critique relates to the need for a modeler to have a better understanding of the data and model vs. just the raw performance. In real-world scenarios - models are often only as good as they are understood by others.

Performance of my Approach¶

My approach yielded about an 80% accuracy rating on its submission, which was fairly good performance despite the mentioned lack of extensive data processing and imputation. This accuracy rating was within 2-4% of the top performing submissions at the time that I took to launch and submit this project, which is encouraging. I'll likely revisit this model at some point to try and get my performance up to the highest it can be by implementing the critiques mentioned above.
